metadata.name: BWEEPS  #203
metadata.description:
A minimalist, black-and-white generative profile picture (PFP) created to commemorate one-year anniversary of Bwople project by Gengoya. The artwork is derived from an initial sketch of Bwople which, despite being not the one that was chosen, still managed to captivate interests. The project provides a unique glimpse into an alternate universe in which Bwople could have been represented.

All images are hand-drawn work by Gengoya and composed by Vector Recite using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool.

To download the full size image on fx(hash):
- Click "open" below the image
- Left click on the image, a "Download image" button will appear on the bottom right.
- Click the "Download image" button.

metadata.name: Oscillators #240
metadata.description:
Click anywhere on the oscillator to play/pause.

3 Rules of Oscillators:
RULE 1, Oscillators should be viewed on Desktop (this is due to the way an oscillator is formed, it requires the display density of the device to be 2 pixels).
RULE 2, Oscillators should be viewed live and not as static images.
RULE 3, Oscillators should be run with the sound on.

Press "S" to Save a version of the Canvas (must be in fullscreen mode)

You are in a dark cave in the Johto region, the year is 1999...

Two synthesizers play a graceful melody atop the shimmering sound of a french horn. A cello provides a deep and haunting counterpoint.

Created with Tone.js and p5js.

Thank you to https://github.com/nbrosowsky/tonejs-instruments for the french horn and cello samples.

metadata.name: CHAOS AND COSMOS - Cosmology of oneself v2 #57
metadata.description:
“There is only one corner of the universe you can be certain of improving, and that’s your own self - Aldous Huxley

Each person contains a cosmos made up of many elements in constant motion and transformation.

I evolved the algorithm of the "cosmology of oneself" project:
-Introduced the black background and some new color palettes
-Changed the proportions of the circles
-Changed the size of the symbols
-Introduced a texture for the background

Everything is generated with code.
This work uses p5.js library and c2.js library.

metadata.name: Canyons #140
metadata.description:
Canyons is an harmony of sweet layers. 

The size, position and frequency of the layers are generated for each token, along with the color theme.  Each layer is masking by a geometric pattern. 
The shapes’s sizes of the patterns are visible as features, like the the number of layers.
  Handmade by code with Javascript, made with fragment.tools 

Quentin Hocdé, Brussels (Belgium), 2022.

objkt.name: A message through the silk road  #17

metadata.name: A message through the silk road  #17
metadata.description:
This work is part of the "Alphabetic Signs" series.

The "Alphabetic Signs" series finds its roots in different places: in my physical work, in a study on letters and typefaces, but also in graffiti and street art.

In this project I codified 11 new symbols that evoke oriental writing, taking inspiration from Japanese, Chinese and Korean symbols.
I coded a dragged "dirty" brush stroke with drops of color.

I reused the fractal component already used in the previous algorithm by inserting the new symbols and mixing new elements.

it is a work of asemic writing, without any semantic meaning.

This work uses p5.js library and p5.scribble.js library.

issuer.name: A message through the silk road

metadata.name: Floating Medusas #17
metadata.description:
Floating Medusas is a generative piece. A group of little creatures creating an organic visual. 

The size, position and frequency of creatures are generated for each token, along with the color theme.  Each creature is masking by a geometric pattern. Creatures have straight or smooth edges.
The shapes’s sizes of the patterns are visible as features, like the edge’s type and the number of creatures.  

Handmade by code with javascript, made with fragment.tools 
Quentin Hocdé, Brussels (Belgium), 2022

metadata.name: CARPE DIEM - millennial loop #18
metadata.description:
"CARPE DIEM" - An instant in a millennial loop

Everything passes in a flash and life is a succession of different moments, sometimes similar, but in any case, all different and unique.
An artwork to reflect on the passage of time and the perception of every moment.

"Carpe Diem" is Latin for "seize the moment".
The work consists of a loop that takes about 1000 years to complete its cycle.
The work is created through 9 cells arranged in a 3x3 matrix which change the symbol they contain every second.

The sequence of the images is not random but has a predetermined order.
The sequence has been planned through the use of prime numbers, so the first cell loops on 5 symbols, the second on 7 symbols, the third on 11 symbols and so forth with the last loop made up of 31 symbols.
In this way it is possible to calculate the exact combination expected at a certain point in time. The set of 9 cells generates always different combinations that are repeated every 33 billion seconds, therefore every 1059 years or so.

"Seize the moment" because every moment, every second, every combination is different from the previous, like every moment of one’s life, even if sometimes certain combinations seem similar.
When a 1059-year cycle closes and as soon as the next loop begins, all 9 cells—each containing a different symbol—line up perfectly. At that precise moment "CARPE DIEM" (9 characters) can be read for a single second only.  Will you be there to read it?

A timer will show the seconds that remain to close the cycle, which will end exactly on October 31st, 2022 at 20:00 (Timezone GMT+0). The next cycle will end January 31, 3082.

Are you ready to observe the alignment of the letters? 
Carpe diem.

This work uses p5.js library.

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #163
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan
